Yeah, that sounds like a plan. Let's do it.

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:28.540
Awesome. All right. So before we get into what you have in your book and some of the other stuff you have going on to achieve that goal, let's just start at the beginning.

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:29.980
What's your story? How did you get into programming?

00:03:29.980 --> 00:03:32.420
Ah, gosh, let's see. How did I get into programming?

00:03:32.420 --> 00:03:49.020
I think, you know, probably way back when I was a kid, I think, you know, the first thing that I remember that really got me inspired to program was going into a, like a survey course in maybe like junior high school or elementary school where we had some Apple IIEs.

00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:55.300
And this is the first time I saw one of those computers and we're learning the basics of programming and basic.

00:03:55.300 --> 00:04:02.180
And I remember having this floppy disk with me and I was like, I was just so fascinated by this idea that you could actually program a computer.

00:04:02.180 --> 00:04:07.680
I mean, I didn't even really know much about computers at that point, but it just, it just seems so intriguing to me.

00:04:07.740 --> 00:04:14.300
So I remember having this disk where I had all these little silly programs that I wrote and, you know, I started to have these aspirations of,

00:04:14.300 --> 00:04:17.520
of building games, of building, building something with it.

00:04:17.520 --> 00:04:22.740
I think I didn't really have an opportunity, you know, not, not too many people have an Apple IIe.

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:31.700
So I didn't really have an opportunity to do much with that until a few years later when, you know, home PCs were becoming more, more of a thing.

00:04:31.700 --> 00:04:35.220
And I remember finding, you know, getting, getting a home PC.

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:42.300
And the first thing kind of that I did when my dad brought home the home PC was I found QBasic on there.

00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:44.720
And I started playing around with that.

00:04:45.480 --> 00:04:46.160
No, that's awesome.

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:58.000
You started out with this exploratory experience with basic and QBasic, you know, and how did you go from that into, I want to make this my career.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.320
This is super interesting and actually getting into programming for real.

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:02.120
Yeah.

00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:06.680
So I think from there, you know, once I had gotten a home computer, I was just, I just hooked.

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:11.740
I was, I wasn't programming at that point, but I was, I loved computer games.

00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:15.320
I had been, you know, playing Atari, Nintendo, all that stuff.

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:23.160
And here was this, this computer that even more powerful, I remember playing, you know, Sierra online or Sierra games and all that.

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:27.380
And I liked the idea of, of creating my own game.

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:31.260
And that's, that's kind of something that I think really drove me.

00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:42.260
I remember spending a lot of time online playing a mud, these multi-user dungeons, kind of the precursor to the EverQuest and the WoW, where it's just a text-based game.

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:43.180
Those were great.

00:05:43.180 --> 00:05:45.020
Which ones, which ones did you play?

00:05:45.240 --> 00:05:45.480
Do you recall?

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:46.480
Oh gosh.

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:50.460
Like, well, there was, I remember playing just through Telnet, right?

00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:50.900
Oh yeah.

00:05:50.900 --> 00:05:52.540
I had this dial-up BBS, right?

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:55.040
And it actually had internet access.

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:01.460
So you dial up to the BBS and then you could actually get Telnet access from the BBS system.

00:06:01.460 --> 00:06:08.560
And, and then I would find mud listings and I'd Telnet into Deku muds and all the different variations.

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:09.280
I can't even remember.

00:06:09.660 --> 00:06:11.280
I didn't like LP muds that much.

00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:11.940
Yeah, that's cool.

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:14.560
I remember my friends and I played this one called Shadow's Edge.

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:16.820
I think it was pretty, pretty popular.

00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:19.240
I, those, those were really interesting days.

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:27.800
Those were the days when William Gibson was talking about cyberspace and the world seemed like, even though it's so bizarre, it was so basic and text-based.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.440
And yet it seemed almost like there was more possible.

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:31.440
Exactly.

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:32.060
Yeah.

00:06:32.060 --> 00:06:33.100
How funny, huh?

00:06:33.100 --> 00:06:33.320
Yeah.

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:41.500
I just remember, you know, sitting at the terminal, you know, and, and thinking, imagine, you know, there's, there's Telnet and then I was like, and then there's gopher protocol.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:48.620
And I was like, just thinking like, gosh, it's so much, it's, it felt like this cyberspace to me.

00:06:48.620 --> 00:06:49.160
It really did.

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:53.480
It felt like there's this huge universe out there that I can access via text.

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:54.940
And it was awesome.

00:06:54.940 --> 00:07:04.780
And I remember even playing a mud that was in, there was this BBS system called Major BBS and so they had this major mud that was part of the BBS system.

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:16.200
And, and actually, you know, it's kind of funny about that is that that was perhaps the most complex program I had written at that time was I remember being in high school and I couldn't play the game all day.

00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:20.120
But I found this, this program called Terminate.

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:25.160
It was a, to connect to the BBS, I forget what they, what they call it, a client essentially.

00:07:25.160 --> 00:07:27.060
And it was programmable.

00:07:27.060 --> 00:07:33.020
And so I wrote a script to play the game while I was at school.

00:07:33.020 --> 00:07:39.060
So basically, you know, I'd run this script and while I was at school, it would connect to the BBS.

00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:41.700
It would go in, log into the game.

00:07:41.700 --> 00:07:43.780
It would run around and, you know, kill things.

00:07:43.780 --> 00:07:45.880
And so I'd be gaining experience and getting levels.

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:49.320
And then every like hour or two, the BBS would disconnect you.

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:54.440
So it would handle that and redial in and, and keep trying to dial in until it got, got in.

00:07:54.440 --> 00:08:04.260
And, and so that was, yeah, that, those days were just, it was, it was like being a pioneer, you know, it's like there was, it was such a magical time, I think.

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:13.760
And that's what really, really got me interested in technology and development is like, I wanted to be part of, I wanted to be creating that world that intrigued me so much.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:14.740
Yeah, that's really cool.

00:08:14.740 --> 00:08:19.100
You know, you're sort of destined to be a programmer when you start solving your problems in code.

00:08:19.180 --> 00:08:24.380
Even if your problems are, I'm really tired of these sort of mundane tasks I got to do in a mud to level up.

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:24.560
Right.

00:08:24.560 --> 00:08:25.040
Exactly.

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:25.700
Yeah.

00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:26.440
Nice.

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:34.440
So maybe let's talk a little bit about like the, your career in terms of your experiences and so on.

00:08:34.440 --> 00:08:37.920
So that people get a sense of what, where you're coming from, I guess.

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:41.080
So you started out as like a lot of us do as a full-time employee.

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:41.480
Is that right?

00:08:41.480 --> 00:08:42.160
That's correct.

00:08:42.160 --> 00:08:42.380
Yeah.

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:43.780
Yeah.

00:08:43.780 --> 00:08:46.160
I started out with a lot of different jobs.

00:08:46.160 --> 00:08:52.680
You know, I think I went to school to Boise State University for a year.

00:08:52.680 --> 00:09:04.920
I almost dropped out of programming because computer science, I went, I remember my first Java class and it was like, we're hand rolling iterators and doing sorting algorithms.

00:09:04.920 --> 00:09:08.360
And I was like, this is not, this is not what I signed up for.

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:09.120
This is not fun.

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:12.580
If this is my life, if this is what programming is, I don't want to do it.

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:13.880
Like I want to make games.

00:09:13.880 --> 00:09:14.980
There is no game.

00:09:14.980 --> 00:09:25.600
There is no fun in like implementing a database engine without conditionals or some bizarre, you know, homework exercise you get, right?

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:26.300
Exactly.

00:09:26.300 --> 00:09:29.600
So I was kind of distraught and it was, it was hard.

00:09:29.600 --> 00:09:30.280
It was boring.

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:37.040
And I remember, you know, during my summer vacation, I got the summer job working as a tester at HP.

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:45.520
And strangely enough, the guy that interviewed me, he was like, one of the interview's questions, I kid you not, was, have you played EverQuest?

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:48.580
And I was like, no, I'm not really.

00:09:48.580 --> 00:09:51.080
He's like, would you be interested in playing EverQuest?

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:52.860
And I was like, well, yeah, definitely.

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:54.780
It's like a graphical mud.

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:55.100
Yeah.

00:09:55.100 --> 00:09:55.640
Hell yeah.

00:09:55.640 --> 00:09:57.680
And so I think that's why I got hired.

00:09:57.680 --> 00:09:58.800
That's awesome.

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:00.820
That's a really cool benefit of the job.

00:10:00.820 --> 00:10:01.060
Yeah.

00:10:01.060 --> 00:10:01.660
Very nice.

00:10:01.660 --> 00:10:02.300
Yeah.

00:10:02.300 --> 00:10:05.800
So these guys, you know, that they were all into EverQuest.

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:10.140
But I, I, essentially that was my first job, like real job.

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:15.520
And I ended up, you know, I was a tester, but I ended up like figuring out ways I could do development.

00:10:15.520 --> 00:10:19.100
I learned PostScript, the printer language, PCL.

00:10:19.100 --> 00:10:23.640
And I started modifying the scripts they're using for, for running the tests.

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:27.880
And I ended up not going back to school because I was making enough money.

00:10:27.880 --> 00:10:38.240
I got a couple of promotions where I was like, well, you know, when I get out of school, I was hoping to make, like, I don't know, at that time, I think I was hoping to make like maybe $40,000 or $50,000 a year.

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:41.660
And that's what I was making at my job, my summer job.

00:10:41.660 --> 00:10:42.680
So I just stayed there.

00:10:43.400 --> 00:10:50.820
And then from there, I ended up moving into a full-time development position at HP.

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:53.400
And I moved around a lot.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:55.780
I did a lot of consulting and contracting.

00:10:55.780 --> 00:11:02.880
I worked for Xerox, small startup companies that went under as I moved around.

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:11.340
I pretty much moved around the country as a, you know, basically as an, either a full-time employee directly for a company or a contractor,

00:11:11.340 --> 00:11:23.540
which was essentially, you know, more of the, not, not the freelancer contractor route, but the staff augmentation where, you know, you're paid an hourly rate by, and you're working for a single company.

00:11:23.540 --> 00:11:28.100
But I pretty much did that for, for a pretty good bulk of my career.

00:11:28.100 --> 00:11:28.780
Right.

00:11:28.780 --> 00:11:32.200
And I think, you know, that's, those are great jobs.

00:11:32.200 --> 00:11:33.800
And they're, they're very interesting.

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:37.040
And what we're going to talk about totally applies to that as well.

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:40.460
But since then, you've gone to do some more independent things, right?

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:48.420
Like, one thing that really blew my mind is you said that you had created a number of online courses.

00:11:48.420 --> 00:11:51.700
And that number and the timeframe really blew my mind.

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:56.420
Like, as me creating my online courses for my, my training company, I know how much work it is.

00:11:56.420 --> 00:11:59.900
Can you talk a bit about your, your online course venture you went on?

00:11:59.900 --> 00:12:00.500
Oh, sure.

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:00.800
Yeah.

00:12:00.900 --> 00:12:13.360
So at some point, you know, to kind of, to kind of cut the fast forward to the, in the story, like, you know, after being an employee for, for some time, I started to get some entrepreneurial type of ideas in my head.

00:12:13.360 --> 00:12:17.420
And so I started to run into some people that were not doing the regular nine to five thing.

00:12:17.420 --> 00:12:19.780
And so, and different things changed my life.

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:24.660
I finally got to this point where I call it like, I think the transition was, was becoming a finisher.

00:12:24.660 --> 00:12:25.720
Okay.

00:12:25.820 --> 00:12:33.320
You know, instead of just starting things and not finishing them, I had a real good dedication that I started to develop of, I finished what I start.

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:35.420
And that made a huge difference in my life.

00:12:35.780 --> 00:12:37.400
And I got some opportunities.

00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:41.940
I started the Simple Programmer blog, which was just my personal blog at the time.

00:12:41.940 --> 00:12:44.320
And opportunities kept coming my way from it.

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:47.720
And one of those opportunities was from this company called Pluralsight.

00:12:47.720 --> 00:12:51.540
And they had mostly .NET training.

00:12:51.540 --> 00:12:57.740
But I was doing, I had just built an Android app and an iOS app as I was playing around with that.

00:12:57.740 --> 00:13:02.480
And they said, hey, you know, do you want to teach a course on Android?

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:03.720
Do you think you could teach a course on Android?

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.000
And I thought, well, you know, I've never taught an online course.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:08.460
I don't even know how to record a course.

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:10.260
But sure, I'll, you know, submit a demo.

00:13:10.260 --> 00:13:12.000
And so I submitted a demo.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:13.320
And they said, oh, this is great.

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:14.520
Yeah, let's, let's do it.

00:13:14.520 --> 00:13:15.980
We'll, we'll commission you for a course.

00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:18.540
And so I did that course.

00:13:18.540 --> 00:13:20.420
And that course went really well.

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:22.840
And, you know, I got my first royalty check.

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:29.600
And I think at that point, it was maybe, I mean, they paid me like a few thousand dollars to do the course or something like that.

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:31.160
And I got the first royalty check.

00:13:31.160 --> 00:13:35.280
And I think it was like a, maybe like three or $4,000, maybe $5,000.

00:13:35.280 --> 00:13:40.120
And I thought, wow, I'm getting paid for work that I did before.

00:13:40.120 --> 00:13:40.780
Yeah.

00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:42.480
Like, and I'll keep getting paid for this work.

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:43.800
This is awesome.

00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:46.340
There's, there's, there's something here, right?

00:13:46.340 --> 00:13:50.600
So I said, man, I can, I need to take advantage of this opportunity as much as I can.

00:13:50.600 --> 00:13:53.220
So I said, what other courses do you need?

00:13:53.220 --> 00:13:55.160
And they said, well, do you know anything about iOS?

00:13:55.160 --> 00:13:59.820
And I said, a little bit, but in two weeks, I'll know a whole lot more.

00:14:00.520 --> 00:14:06.340
So I studied hard, you know, started really learning as much as I could, crunching it, all the, everything that I could learn about it.

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:07.620
And I put out an iOS course.

00:14:07.620 --> 00:14:09.800
And then I asked, what other courses do you need?

00:14:09.800 --> 00:14:13.280
And, you know, I ended up building quite a few courses.

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:16.960
And then as I started building these courses, I started building a system.

00:14:17.040 --> 00:14:19.580
I started getting better at it and faster at it.

00:14:19.580 --> 00:14:23.280
At the same time, I started, you know, the royalty checks were increasing.

00:14:23.280 --> 00:14:26.760
And I started to realize, like, there's a really huge opportunity here.

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:31.200
And there's a lot of authors already, but they're not taking advantage of this opportunity.

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:34.440
You know, they're, they're taking like three months to put out a course and stuff.

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:40.460
I got to figure out how to do this fast, how to do this efficient, and how to have a high quality course.

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:54.140
And so over the, I think over, what is it, like, gosh, it ended up being over a three-year period, I put out 55 full-length courses that are around, you know, on average three to five hours in length.

00:14:54.140 --> 00:14:59.780
And I basically, for, gosh, I saw this as my ticket out.

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:07.260
I saw this as a way, as I started doing the numbers, I was like, okay, if I can do this, if I can hold down my full-time job.

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:15.380
And I remember having this conversation with my wife because she was, she was on board with me doing the pluralside thing, but she wasn't sure about, you know, how much time I was going to spend.

00:15:15.380 --> 00:15:18.220
But I told her, I was like, okay, look, here's my plan.

00:15:18.220 --> 00:15:20.020
I'm going to do my full-time job.

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:23.660
And every night I'm going to work like four or five hours every night.

00:15:23.660 --> 00:15:24.940
You're not going to see much of me.

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:31.000
Every weekend I'm going to be working, but I'm going to do this for like a year or two years and we'll be set for life.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:31.480
Right.

00:15:31.480 --> 00:15:34.640
That was, you know, I had done the math and this, this worked out.

00:15:34.640 --> 00:15:45.800
And so my life for, for two years was basically just, I mean, I don't want to say it was hell, but it was, there was nothing, there was no recreation in there and no vacation.

00:15:45.800 --> 00:15:48.060
It was, it was the grind, right?

00:15:48.060 --> 00:15:49.020
It was, it was grind.

00:15:49.020 --> 00:15:51.160
But I worked and I worked hard.

00:15:51.160 --> 00:15:54.680
I was putting out blog posts and still running my business at the same time.

00:15:54.680 --> 00:15:58.640
And I mean, I was working probably 80, 90 hour weeks for probably two years.

00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:07.180
And I ended up putting out maybe something like, I think it was 20 courses or so over that time, doing it part time.

00:16:07.460 --> 00:16:13.480
And then after that had happened, my checks got to the point where I could quit my full-time job.

00:16:13.480 --> 00:16:15.160
So I quit my job.

00:16:15.160 --> 00:16:19.060
I told my boss, I was like, I love working here, but it just doesn't make sense.

00:16:19.060 --> 00:16:21.560
My, you know, I'm able to make enough money from royalty check.

00:16:21.560 --> 00:16:23.740
That's more than, than the salary you're paying me.

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:26.020
And he said, well, you should have quit earlier.

00:16:26.020 --> 00:16:28.140
And so I went for one year.

00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:29.160
I did full-time.

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:34.440
I said, okay, what I'm going to do this year is I'm just going to full-time create Pluralsight courses.

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:40.040
And aside from doing blog posts and YouTube videos and stuff, that's my focus.

00:16:40.040 --> 00:16:48.520
So I went independent and I created, in that year, my goal was to create 30, 30 Pluralsight courses.

00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:50.740
I created 36 Pluralsight courses.

