Yeah, yeah, it's really interesting.

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:20.420
I've got two kind of thoughts on that, like two things that are kind of almost contradictory information.

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:26.480
But as a developer, having a mortgage, having a family or whatever, and having a job, having a career already,

00:19:26.480 --> 00:19:28.640
I think that's absolutely the way to go.

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:33.860
And that's what I recommend to everyone is like don't – you have an idea.

00:19:33.860 --> 00:19:34.820
You quit your job.

00:19:34.820 --> 00:19:37.400
You got a couple months savings.

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:40.200
You're throwing it all on the line on one shot.

00:19:40.200 --> 00:19:41.840
You don't even know marketing.

00:19:41.840 --> 00:19:45.820
And that's going to be the most important thing is building an audience of marketing.

00:19:45.820 --> 00:19:47.660
You don't even know that part, right?

00:19:47.660 --> 00:19:49.260
And you've got a gun to your head.

00:19:49.260 --> 00:19:54.240
This is a horrible situation in order to – you've got to figure your first business is going to fail.

00:19:54.240 --> 00:19:56.100
You've got to figure you're going to have a big learning curve.

00:19:56.100 --> 00:19:57.840
You've got to have some runway.

00:19:57.840 --> 00:20:05.640
So I think – and plus, I think most people don't realize what it's actually like to work really hard.

00:20:05.920 --> 00:20:10.180
And I don't say that to slight people or to belittle anyone.

00:20:10.180 --> 00:20:17.440
But when I started doing a full-time job and working part-time doing the Pluralsight,

00:20:17.440 --> 00:20:20.600
I realized, man, I've been sandbagging it for a while.

00:20:20.600 --> 00:20:23.160
There's a huge difference.

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:31.160
And even the kind of stuff that I do now, it's like there's a huge – you've got to really check yourself to make sure that you can do that.

00:20:31.260 --> 00:20:37.720
Because I know plenty of people that have quit their job and like, okay, now I have eight hours a day to get my work – to work on my business.

00:20:37.720 --> 00:20:41.620
And they go to Starbucks and they work like an hour.

00:20:41.620 --> 00:20:45.840
And that's – and it's just because you've got to get that discipline.

00:20:46.540 --> 00:20:49.880
So I think that's, you know, what you said is absolutely critical.

00:20:49.880 --> 00:20:55.080
Most people should be – like if you can't build a business on the side, you can't build a business full-time.

00:20:55.080 --> 00:21:02.180
I firmly believe that because if you don't have what it takes to work a full-time job and to build a business at the same time,

00:21:02.180 --> 00:21:04.620
you don't have what it takes to build a business, period.

00:21:04.620 --> 00:21:06.520
It requires that much.

00:21:06.520 --> 00:21:07.920
And it's not for everyone.

00:21:07.920 --> 00:21:10.360
But if you're going to do it, you've got to be able to do that.

00:21:10.360 --> 00:21:16.020
And then the other thing that I say, though, kind of the contradictory side of it is if I were young,

00:21:16.020 --> 00:21:24.680
if I were like 18, 19, just starting out, I would never – I would like – I would go and move to Thailand and, you know,

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:28.360
Chiang Mai or something like that where it's like $500 a month cost of living.

00:21:28.360 --> 00:21:34.820
Or I'd find like a roommate situation where my – I would get my living expenses to be under $1,000 a month.

00:21:34.820 --> 00:21:38.920
There's ways to live under $1,000 a month, under $500 a month if I could.

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:42.640
And I would just focus everything on building an online business.

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:49.700
Because as soon as you hit the point where if your expenses are $1,000 a month and you build a business that generates $1,000 a month,

00:21:49.700 --> 00:21:59.560
which is really not that hard, it can be done certainly in a year by anyone that's willing to really go at it, you're free for life.

00:22:00.040 --> 00:22:03.520
Now, you're not going to make as much money in the short term.

00:22:03.520 --> 00:22:07.420
But in the long term, you know, that's what I would recommend.

00:22:07.420 --> 00:22:09.320
But I think it's two different paths.

00:22:09.320 --> 00:22:16.400
You know, if you're already down the path, like you've got – at 18, 19, you've got nothing to lose going that route.

00:22:16.840 --> 00:22:22.400
At like, you know, in your late 20s or 30s, you've got a family, you've got a mortgage, you've got, you know, people that depend on you.

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:23.800
You've got a lot to lose.

00:22:23.800 --> 00:22:29.640
So you can't take that kind of a – you know, you can't be a vagabond and take that kind of risk.

00:22:29.640 --> 00:22:30.460
Yeah, I agree.

00:22:30.460 --> 00:22:33.620
I really wish I had thought about some of these things when I was younger.

00:22:33.620 --> 00:22:35.020
But, you know, it's still – it's all good.

00:22:36.020 --> 00:22:48.100
One thing, though, I'd like to maybe take it back to is like as we maybe could move a little bit into your book is we're talking about this move into entrepreneurship and how amazing I think it is in you as well.

00:22:48.100 --> 00:22:54.100
But what we're talking about I think really applies across the board, especially your book applies across the board.

00:22:54.100 --> 00:22:58.720
Like even if you just work at a company with 20,000 employees doing software development, right?

00:22:59.620 --> 00:23:09.600
So one of the quotes I like from your book is you said – you quoted someone and says, the biggest mistake that you can make is to believe that you're working for someone else.

00:23:09.600 --> 00:23:11.120
You know, job security is gone.

00:23:11.120 --> 00:23:13.760
The driving force of a career must come from the individual.

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:16.780
Jobs are owned by the company, but you own your career.

00:23:16.780 --> 00:23:25.100
And I think that really sets the stage well for shifting the focus of what you need to do long term.

00:23:25.100 --> 00:23:27.000
Yeah, yeah, I totally agree.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:34.780
You know, I think that the thing is that you have to have the mindset that you are a business, right?

00:23:34.780 --> 00:23:39.900
That you are the business, not that you're an employee, whether you're an employee or not.

00:23:39.900 --> 00:23:49.280
Because really, you know, and I always tell developers that if you're an employee of a company, that just means that you own a business that has one customer, right?

00:23:49.280 --> 00:23:56.340
And the reason why that mindset is so important is because it changes the way that you think about everything, right?

00:23:56.480 --> 00:24:05.480
You know, there's a whole different mindset between I go to work and I clock in and then I get my paycheck and that's owed to me.

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:07.440
It's almost an entitled attitude.

00:24:07.440 --> 00:24:18.520
You know, it's not quite – you know, it's not like you expect to get something for nothing, but you expect that if you just show up and you are there doing your work that you get a paycheck.

00:24:19.140 --> 00:24:20.980
And that's not really how the world works.

00:24:20.980 --> 00:24:25.820
It's an abstraction above the real economics of the world.

00:24:25.820 --> 00:24:32.920
The real way that the world works is that you create some kind of product or service or some value for people and people pay you for that.

00:24:33.300 --> 00:24:36.720
And so underlying every single business is this model.

00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:41.980
We just create this abstraction over it when we're an employee and expect that hours equals pay.

00:24:41.980 --> 00:24:47.360
But that's – as an entrepreneur, you know that you can put in a lot of hours and that might not equal pay.

00:24:47.720 --> 00:24:54.860
But underneath whatever environment that you're working in, whatever company it is, they have the reality of the situation.

00:24:54.860 --> 00:24:57.360
It doesn't matter if you're in a large company or a small company.

00:24:57.360 --> 00:25:00.420
That company creates some kind of value.

00:25:00.420 --> 00:25:02.860
It creates some kind of product, some kind of service.

00:25:02.860 --> 00:25:06.940
You're part of that creation and that's where the money comes from.

00:25:07.940 --> 00:25:16.920
So when you're divorced from that and you don't realize that and you don't have that mindset, you're disconnecting yourself from a lot of opportunity and ways that you can grow your career.

00:25:16.920 --> 00:25:25.360
And so even if you don't want to be an entrepreneur, just as an employee, just having this mindset of realizing that you are a business and this is how the economic model works.

00:25:25.360 --> 00:25:26.480
This is how the system works.

00:25:26.480 --> 00:25:29.220
It gives you more opportunities to explore.

00:25:29.220 --> 00:25:38.520
It gives you the thinking to say, well, if I market myself, if I build a blog, if I create – if I become more valuable as a developer, I can make more money.

00:25:38.520 --> 00:25:44.120
I can – there's more opportunities out there than just work, get paid for those hours.

00:25:44.120 --> 00:25:46.500
You know, there's a whole range of possibility.

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:51.020
And you start thinking about, well, okay, this company that I work for, well, let's see.

00:25:51.020 --> 00:25:53.920
You know, if I think of them as my client, how can I make my client better?

00:25:53.920 --> 00:25:55.340
How can I make them more money?

00:25:55.500 --> 00:25:59.980
Would they be willing to give me part of the money that I'm able to make them?

00:25:59.980 --> 00:26:01.500
Maybe, right?

00:26:01.500 --> 00:26:02.960
You've got more opportunities.

00:26:02.960 --> 00:26:06.760
So I think that's, you know, critical to shift that mindset.

00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:08.780
It's definitely a big mind shift.

00:26:08.780 --> 00:26:16.340
And I think, like you say, it really is important, you know, to go back to this value, you create sort of trading value for money.

00:26:16.340 --> 00:26:21.420
When you're a business, there's a very sort of continuous curve.

00:26:21.620 --> 00:26:25.860
Today I sold X number of widgets or N number of courses.

00:26:25.860 --> 00:26:34.760
And then the next day – so you have like a really fine curve that you can actually see sales going up, sales going down, expenses going up, expenses going down.

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:39.800
But when you're an employee, I feel like the same curve applies, but it's discrete.

00:26:40.940 --> 00:26:42.660
Like the way you feel it is discrete.

00:26:42.660 --> 00:26:47.260
You get the same amount of money and either you get a raise, you get a promotion, or you don't.

00:26:47.260 --> 00:26:50.420
Or you get demoted or let go, or you don't.

00:26:50.420 --> 00:26:51.800
But there's only like three or four steps.

00:26:51.800 --> 00:26:55.620
It's not like a continuous sort of curve on a real number scale.

00:26:55.620 --> 00:26:57.380
But the curve is still there.

00:26:57.380 --> 00:27:03.580
And, you know, you've got to really be thinking as if the curve was continuous even though it's not.

00:27:04.380 --> 00:27:06.860
So your book – let's talk a little bit about your book.

00:27:06.860 --> 00:27:08.880
So your book is called Soft Skills.

00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:10.680
What's the full title?

00:27:10.680 --> 00:27:11.020
I'm sorry.

00:27:11.020 --> 00:27:11.940
I don't have it pulled up right now.

00:27:11.940 --> 00:27:14.760
Oh, Soft Skills, the Software Developer's Life Manual.

00:27:14.760 --> 00:27:15.380
Yes.

00:27:15.380 --> 00:27:20.660
And I think it's a super interesting take on helping developers with their career.

00:27:20.660 --> 00:27:24.560
because there's a ton of career books about like general career.

00:27:24.560 --> 00:27:31.300
And there's a ton of software developer books like here's how you call a function with name parameters

00:27:31.300 --> 00:27:33.480
and Objective-C or something weird like that.

00:27:33.480 --> 00:27:40.400
But the sort of I'm going to take and focus on career specifically for software developer

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:41.600
and technical folks.

00:27:41.600 --> 00:27:44.960
I think that's a really valuable book and niche that you filled there.

00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:49.620
So the first thing you start with is this business mindset that we already talked about.

00:27:49.620 --> 00:27:52.960
The next thing is focusing on people skills.

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:58.440
And, you know, like the idea is a lot of us feel like we should be able to just write code.

00:27:58.440 --> 00:28:01.640
Hey, my code is cleaner than anyone else's or whatever.

00:28:01.640 --> 00:28:05.340
So I should be advancing in my career.

00:28:05.340 --> 00:28:07.400
But that's not necessarily true, right?

00:28:07.400 --> 00:28:09.600
So what are you talking about with people skills?

00:28:09.600 --> 00:28:10.260
Right.

00:28:10.460 --> 00:28:16.400
I think that it turns out that the most valuable thing that helped me in my career

00:28:16.400 --> 00:28:22.660
and that as I work with developers and hear their stories and successes is not the technical skills.

00:28:22.660 --> 00:28:28.140
It turns out to be it's all those the soft skills, the other skills, right, which I talk about in the book.

00:28:28.140 --> 00:28:37.360
But people skills in general tends to be one of the biggest areas of leverage of where a lot of developers lack these skills.

00:28:37.360 --> 00:28:38.660
And they think they don't need those skills.

00:28:38.660 --> 00:28:41.220
They think that being technically competent is enough.

00:28:41.740 --> 00:28:45.400
And maybe, I mean, I say maybe, but I know that it's not true.

00:28:45.400 --> 00:28:48.340
I say maybe back in the day that that was true.

00:28:48.340 --> 00:28:50.340
But it's never been true, right?

00:28:50.380 --> 00:28:59.060
Because if you look at in the industrial age, you know, the industrial barons and stuff and you read some of their writings and memoirs and stuff,

00:28:59.060 --> 00:29:02.720
you find, again, that people skills is more important than technical skills.

00:29:02.720 --> 00:29:12.220
But specifically in our field, especially today, we have hit this point where software development, programming itself,

00:29:12.220 --> 00:29:18.300
is going through a period which I think is almost becoming commoditized, right?

00:29:18.300 --> 00:29:27.580
We have plenty of places we can go online to find programmers that will program and they're real good at it for very low hourly wages.

00:29:27.580 --> 00:29:38.100
So why would a company, why would a person hire a programmer today and pay them, you know, the kind of salaries that we would like to get?

00:29:38.100 --> 00:29:43.740
And part of that is because or a majority of that is because of their communication, because of their people skills,

00:29:43.740 --> 00:29:45.700
because they don't just program.

00:29:46.180 --> 00:29:48.060
They can get along with the team.

00:29:48.060 --> 00:29:51.700
They can express their ideas and opinions.

00:29:51.700 --> 00:29:54.180
They know how to interact.

00:29:54.180 --> 00:29:55.140
They know how to communicate.

00:29:55.140 --> 00:29:58.060
They know how to make the team better.

00:29:58.060 --> 00:30:02.040
And so I think that's a critical, critical skill.

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:08.880
And if you think about it just, you know, from an employee perspective, if you want to get ahead in your career, if you want to get ahead in your job,

00:30:08.960 --> 00:30:13.980
a lot of people say, oh, well, you know, sure, I could be a brown noser or kiss up to the boss.

00:30:13.980 --> 00:30:15.680
And that's not what people skills are.

00:30:15.680 --> 00:30:18.820
It's about being able to make your team more effective.

00:30:18.820 --> 00:30:27.420
It's being able to understand humans and interact with them in such a way that you're able to not just, you know, code,

00:30:27.420 --> 00:30:34.720
but communicate the ideas, make the team better, get everyone on board, align people in the same direction.

00:30:34.720 --> 00:30:38.380
And so those things are all really, really important.

00:30:38.660 --> 00:30:46.320
Because if you think about it, as a software developer, at least in most places I've worked, most of your time is not spent writing code.

00:30:46.320 --> 00:30:53.260
A lot of your time is writing emails and meetings, communicating your ideas to coworkers, having discussions.

00:30:53.260 --> 00:30:57.060
These are the things that you actually spend most of your time doing.

00:30:57.060 --> 00:31:05.780
And so if you're not good at those things, then, you know, most of your job, the most leveraged, effective part of your job, you're lacking in.

00:31:05.780 --> 00:31:09.760
So I think people skills are definitely a really important component.

00:31:09.760 --> 00:31:12.120
And it just helps you in your life in general.

00:31:12.120 --> 00:31:18.320
I mean, you know, when you're talking to someone, when you're trying to get a raise, when you're, if you're someone that can be put in front of a customer,

00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:27.900
if you know what motivates a person and how to get them motivated, you're going to have a lot more success in getting what you want.

00:31:27.900 --> 00:31:30.080
Yeah, I think that's definitely true.

00:31:30.080 --> 00:31:34.300
I feel like being a really good programmer these days are kind of table stakes.

00:31:34.940 --> 00:31:37.620
But it's not enough to really win the game.

00:31:37.620 --> 00:31:40.240
You've got to, you've got to do more, right?

00:31:40.240 --> 00:31:48.320
So one of the things that you talked about when you were a full-time employee, it's not an entrepreneurial thing, is keeping your manager really well informed.

00:31:48.320 --> 00:31:52.000
One of the things I sucked at when I was a full-time employee was I would work really hard.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:53.520
I would do amazing stuff.

00:31:53.520 --> 00:31:54.860
I'd ship projects early.

00:31:55.560 --> 00:32:01.040
But I didn't communicate very well what I had done, what I was going to do, and so on.

00:32:01.040 --> 00:32:02.980
So you had a good story about what you did.

00:32:02.980 --> 00:32:06.420
I forget exactly where I came up with the idea.

00:32:06.720 --> 00:32:10.340
But I basically started creating what I called weekly reports.

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:16.100
And what I would do is I think maybe I had this idea because I was put into a role of managing a team.

00:32:16.100 --> 00:32:24.000
And I realized that the main job is managing this team that I just need to know what everyone was doing and working on.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:26.460
And I needed this information so I could relay that information.

00:32:27.020 --> 00:32:31.040
So I remember getting this job and I thought, okay, here's what I'm going to do.

00:32:31.040 --> 00:32:33.760
Every day I'm just going to start writing down.

00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:36.240
I'm going to make a few bullet points of what I did that day.

00:32:36.240 --> 00:32:41.480
And so what I ended up doing was the first week I was there, it was this contract job.

00:32:41.480 --> 00:32:46.300
I sent a weekly report and I had Monday, I did this, I accomplished this.

00:32:46.300 --> 00:32:49.240
And I put it in terms of what I accomplished really, right?

00:32:49.240 --> 00:32:55.900
And I talked about just a few bullet points for every day so that they would know exactly what I did every single day and what I accomplished.

00:32:56.420 --> 00:33:00.320
And I sent that to my manager and I CC'd his manager.

00:33:00.320 --> 00:33:10.380
And I said, and I explained on the first email, I said, look, the reason why I'm doing this is because just in case you're out, you know, and just as a FYI so that you can see what's going on.

00:33:10.380 --> 00:33:12.340
And, you know, I phrased it really well.

00:33:12.340 --> 00:33:19.280
It was, you know, in my mind I was thinking, okay, you know, I want to make sure that I'm getting as much visibility as possible.

00:33:19.280 --> 00:33:21.980
And so, yeah, so that's what I ended up doing.

00:33:21.980 --> 00:33:26.120
And I started doing that, you know, every week they could expect from me to get a weekly report.

00:33:26.320 --> 00:33:28.920
Showing exactly what I did that week.

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:37.260
And it turned out to be a really good move for my career because all the work, like you said, that I was doing, now I was getting credit for.

00:33:37.260 --> 00:33:38.060
Now it was visible.

00:33:38.060 --> 00:33:46.840
And there was no—in fact, one time I remember there was a highly politically charged environment at one of the corporations I was working at.

00:33:47.360 --> 00:33:55.280
And someone had got into a—was trying to maneuver politically and get me into trouble.

00:33:55.280 --> 00:33:58.960
And they accused me of something or of not working on something.

00:33:58.960 --> 00:34:01.580
And we got into a meeting.

00:34:01.580 --> 00:34:04.060
And I had notes.

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:05.900
I had, you know, weekly reports.

00:34:05.900 --> 00:34:13.880
Not just my own personal notes, but weekly reports that had been sent out every single week that said exactly what I did on a particular day.

00:34:13.880 --> 00:34:19.980
That worked out really well for me and not so much for the other person who had no data at all.

00:34:20.480 --> 00:34:23.280
So I think it's a really, really good way.

00:34:23.280 --> 00:34:31.260
And, you know, that's a good—if you think about it, again, this comes back to people skills and thinking like a business is this idea that what does your manager need?

00:34:31.340 --> 00:34:41.060
You know, I always tell developers, your job, right, as a developer or as an employee in any company is to make your manager look as good as possible.

00:34:41.060 --> 00:34:49.000
That's really like if you want to advance in your career, don't try and necessarily make yourself look as good as possible, but make your manager.

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:53.620
And by sending weekly reports, you're helping them to do their job more efficiently.

00:34:53.620 --> 00:34:57.660
And you're really giving them the credit of, okay, because they're in charge of you.

00:34:57.660 --> 00:35:01.180
And so the better that you do, it reflects better on them.

00:35:01.600 --> 00:35:09.280
And so by couching it that way and showing how—giving them the information that they need to be able to do their job better, it's going to make it better for you.

00:35:09.280 --> 00:35:16.600
Yeah, I think that's a really interesting piece of practical advice that would be, you know, totally missing from a lot of career books.

00:35:16.600 --> 00:35:17.940
I think that's great.

