00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:24.660
One of the things that I've tried to help people with on my show, I did a show 39 and 41 about people getting their first job.

00:36:24.660 --> 00:36:32.740
Because I feel like getting into software development, there's a pretty big step to actually get your first job and break in.

00:36:32.740 --> 00:36:40.740
But once you're in, I feel like if you're continually learning, you're probably going to have not a huge problem finding a job.

00:36:40.740 --> 00:36:42.000
I know there's some exceptions to that.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:46.280
But in general, I think the hardest step you take is getting into the industry.

00:36:46.280 --> 00:36:50.460
And so you had some really interesting advice around hacking the interview.

00:36:50.460 --> 00:36:51.180
Yeah.

00:36:51.180 --> 00:36:58.420
So I think that if you just take your resume and apply for a job, that's the worst way to get a job.

00:36:58.420 --> 00:37:02.260
Because you're competing with everyone else because you're just a resume.

00:37:02.260 --> 00:37:04.840
You're just some data point to a company.

00:37:04.840 --> 00:37:10.260
But what I find is, can you figure out a way to go into the back door, right?

00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:20.000
And the best way to get a job, the way that most jobs get filled, a majority of jobs that you don't even see that are even posted, is through referrals, through personal referrals, right?

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:20.820
We hire someone.

00:37:20.820 --> 00:37:25.300
Because, again, you said that it's really hard for someone to get started in the industry.

00:37:25.300 --> 00:37:38.420
And I think primarily the reason why, which I haven't heard too many people say, but honestly, like hiring developers, I think that the main reason is because you're afraid that someone can't actually code.

00:37:39.620 --> 00:37:45.040
And this seems kind of funny, but I remember when the whole FizzBuzz thing was really big.

00:37:45.040 --> 00:37:47.860
And, you know, it was all over the place.

00:37:47.860 --> 00:37:51.440
Like everyone was saying, oh, I can't believe people can't do FizzBuzz.

00:37:51.660 --> 00:37:57.540
And then I interviewed like several developers and they even knew about the FizzBuzz thing.

00:37:57.540 --> 00:37:59.620
And I asked them to do FizzBuzz.

00:37:59.620 --> 00:38:02.840
And they thought that was funny because – but they couldn't do it.

00:38:02.840 --> 00:38:07.380
And I thought to myself, holy crap, this is just crazy.

00:38:07.380 --> 00:38:13.300
Is this really – like, I mean, yeah, I understand that it's under pressure and whatnot.

00:38:13.300 --> 00:38:18.820
But if you know this is going on and you haven't prepared, oh, gosh.

00:38:18.820 --> 00:38:23.660
And so that's the biggest risk is when you hire a developer, can they actually code?

00:38:23.660 --> 00:38:27.520
Maybe they can fix a few bugs, but could they actually write real code?

00:38:27.520 --> 00:38:33.160
Because that can have a huge negative impact and you have to – and you won't even necessarily know it.

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:48.240
So, you know, all that is to say that when someone hires someone, the best way to hire someone is to know – not to get a resume and then see what kind of BS they're going to tell you in an interview.

00:38:48.240 --> 00:38:53.360
But to say if you already know someone, you know someone who knows someone who's an excellent coder, right?

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:54.240
This is a great way.

00:38:54.240 --> 00:38:56.820
This is why personal networks and referrals work so well.

00:38:56.820 --> 00:39:03.680
So, can you figure out some way instead of just submitting your resume blind to get a personal referral?

00:39:03.680 --> 00:39:09.940
Can you – you know, and one of the examples that I use in the book is I wanted to get this remote job, right?

00:39:09.940 --> 00:39:11.520
I wanted to work from home.

00:39:11.520 --> 00:39:19.580
That was my – there was this particular company and I felt like they're a good company and I just – I wanted to get a good job working from home.

00:39:19.580 --> 00:39:24.500
And it was so competitive to get into that company because there's so many people who wanted that job, obviously.

00:39:25.100 --> 00:39:35.560
So, what I did was I started finding some of the developers that worked for that company and I started reading their blogs and I started putting meaningful comments on their blogs.

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:43.060
Not just being lame and just trying to see what I could get but actually contributing to their blogs and getting noticed.

00:39:43.060 --> 00:39:50.800
And after several months worth of time, pretty much all the developers on that team knew who I was because I was this guy that was commenting on their blogs.

00:39:50.800 --> 00:39:52.640
We were having discussions and whatnot.

00:39:52.920 --> 00:39:56.360
And guess what happened the next time that they opened up a job opening?

00:39:56.360 --> 00:40:01.760
Well, not only did I get a personal referral but several developers on that team said,

00:40:01.760 --> 00:40:03.420
Hey, John, you should apply for this job.

00:40:03.420 --> 00:40:09.240
And of course, you know, when I did, they referred me, handed in my resume.

00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:12.780
And then multiple developers on that team said, Oh, I know who that guy is.

00:40:12.780 --> 00:40:13.300
He's awesome.

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:15.660
And so, obviously, I got that job.

00:40:15.660 --> 00:40:20.460
And that's the better way than just submitting your resume.

00:40:20.460 --> 00:40:28.480
You know, you can—you hack the interview process by not having—by having the interviewer know who you are before you go into the interview.

00:40:28.480 --> 00:40:31.440
It's—and that can be done in multiple ways.

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:35.940
You know, I always encourage developers to market themselves, to build a blog, something like that.

00:40:35.940 --> 00:40:44.420
It's great when you go into an interview and you shake the interviewer's hand and they say, Oh, oh, you know, I think I read a blog post that you wrote.

00:40:44.420 --> 00:40:45.340
I know who you are.

00:40:45.340 --> 00:40:52.140
And then instead of having a grueling interview, you have an hour-long conversation because you're already in.

00:40:52.480 --> 00:40:55.760
So, people primarily hire people that they like.

00:40:55.760 --> 00:41:05.500
They figure out—it's weird how, like, you know, we all want to be objective and say that it's a meritocracy and we hire based on technical skill.

00:41:05.500 --> 00:41:16.540
But we have this way, you know, psychologically in our mind of justifying, of saying—of finding someone who we don't like and finding problems why they're—you know, why they're weak technically.

00:41:16.540 --> 00:41:23.000
And someone we do like and finding reasons why they're going to succeed even though they don't know this or making excuses for them.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:30.380
So, you've got to remember that psychology and you've got to get—you really have to build rapport with an interviewer before the interview.

00:41:30.380 --> 00:41:39.660
You know, if you want to go around the back door, not go through the initial—the process that everyone goes through, which is the most difficult way to get hired for a job.

00:41:39.660 --> 00:41:40.480
Yeah, absolutely.

00:41:40.480 --> 00:41:44.080
If you can get a recommendation, it's so much better.

00:41:44.500 --> 00:41:56.600
The companies I've worked for, the point where it becomes a publicly available job where resumes are requested, it would never even make it that far if somebody on the team knew somebody they could recommend.

00:41:56.600 --> 00:41:57.220
Exactly.

00:41:57.220 --> 00:42:02.920
Like, that's like, oh, geez, I guess we're going to have to actually open this up as a job rather than just get a recommendation.

00:42:02.920 --> 00:42:05.460
So, very, very, very important.

00:42:05.460 --> 00:42:15.280
And I think this whole marketing yourself thing is more important than many people realize, even for regular sort of full-time employment situations.

00:42:15.280 --> 00:42:16.880
But let's come back to that in just a minute.

00:42:17.380 --> 00:42:33.560
So, one of the things that you discuss, and I think is a really interesting question people want to figure out for themselves, is should you try to work at a small company where you'll have a broader range of exposure to technology, broader responsibilities, and so on?

00:42:33.560 --> 00:42:39.720
Or at a large company where it might be more focused, but you'll have more people you can work with and depend on and so on?

00:42:39.720 --> 00:42:43.260
What do you think about, like, a small company versus large company?

00:42:43.620 --> 00:42:45.720
You know, I think there's pros and cons to both.

00:42:45.720 --> 00:42:48.500
And, you know, I've worked for both in my career.

00:42:48.500 --> 00:43:00.280
I tend to prefer a small company, especially if you're getting started out, because you get more involved in the business and the economics of it and your hands into more things.

00:43:00.280 --> 00:43:02.180
It's a huge advantage of a small company.

00:43:02.180 --> 00:43:05.260
With big company, and plus you're more visible, right?

00:43:05.260 --> 00:43:07.940
You can't hide in the weeds.

00:43:08.140 --> 00:43:13.920
Like, what you do, both positive and negative, is going to have a direct impact on the bottom line.

00:43:13.920 --> 00:43:21.920
And so, you have this opportunity to actually move the needle and to make a difference and to get exposed to a large variety of things.

00:43:21.920 --> 00:43:25.640
In a big company, you might be able to work on cooler projects, right?

00:43:25.640 --> 00:43:32.000
You might be able to work on things that only a big company could do and you might have more training opportunities and things like that.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:39.960
But, you know, there's nothing like getting the experience, getting that kind of experience that a small company provides.

00:43:39.960 --> 00:43:50.860
So, you know, if I were to say what is ideal as an employee, I would probably say that it's to spend a lot of time at various small companies.

00:43:50.860 --> 00:43:56.420
I think that's—you're going to get the largest volume of experience by doing that.

00:43:56.820 --> 00:43:59.840
But, you know, there's some people that—and it's changing, right?

00:43:59.840 --> 00:44:04.180
You know, there's some people that have worked at Microsoft their entire life or HP.

00:44:04.180 --> 00:44:10.820
I mean, when I was at HP, there were, you know, 30-year—they interned at HP and they just worked at HP for 30 years in development.

00:44:10.820 --> 00:44:14.660
And they made good money and they had good careers.

00:44:14.660 --> 00:44:23.420
But, gosh, that—I mean, can you imagine what would happen if you got laid off after working for 30 years at the same job and you never had any other job experience?

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:25.980
That would be a traumatic life event.

00:44:25.980 --> 00:44:29.580
That would be like having your spouse killed or something like that.

00:44:29.580 --> 00:44:32.580
I mean, that level of trauma, I can imagine.

00:44:32.580 --> 00:44:40.500
So, I would strongly encourage people to at least—at least, you know, if you're starting out, to work at multiple companies.

00:44:40.500 --> 00:44:43.920
And if they're small companies, I think you can gain that experience faster.

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:51.560
And then if you decide you want to go the corporate route and climb the corporate ladder, then maybe you do that later on in your career and then you can—there's time for that.

00:44:51.560 --> 00:44:59.160
But I feel like you get a little bit more benefit out of the smaller companies than you do out of the large.

00:44:59.160 --> 00:45:00.620
Yeah, I tend to agree with you.

00:45:00.740 --> 00:45:10.060
I think one of the caveats of being really successful at a small company is you have to be willing to say things like, I have no idea how to do that.

00:45:10.060 --> 00:45:12.440
But give me two days and I'll figure it out.

00:45:12.880 --> 00:45:22.540
Because you may be the guy or girl who they come to and say, hey, we need to set up a new server and we've got to do SSL and e-commerce.

00:45:22.540 --> 00:45:24.240
And nobody here has ever done that.

00:45:24.240 --> 00:45:27.280
But we've nominated you to do the e-commerce system.

00:45:27.280 --> 00:45:28.780
You're like, well, I've never done it either, right?

00:45:28.880 --> 00:45:35.140
But it's both a huge opportunity that you're given the time, energy, and opportunity to do that.

00:45:35.140 --> 00:45:43.640
But if you don't want to be the person that gets repeatedly thrown into the deep end of some other strange technology, then maybe a larger company would be better for you.

00:45:43.640 --> 00:45:48.380
But if you can embrace it, I feel like you'll really flourish from being in that environment.

00:45:48.380 --> 00:45:49.500
Yeah, yeah, definitely.

00:45:49.500 --> 00:45:51.300
That's—I totally agree.

00:45:51.820 --> 00:45:52.060
Yeah.

00:45:52.060 --> 00:46:00.140
Another thing that you talk about, and maybe this is a good segue towards marketing, is specialization and niches.

00:46:00.140 --> 00:46:09.780
Yeah, I think this is one of those areas that I end up doing the most discussion and talking on because it's a hard pill for many developers to swallow.

00:46:09.780 --> 00:46:21.600
Because a lot of times we're told to be almost generalist, jack-of-all-trades, that being the super developer that can do anything is highly valuable, to have a wide variety of skills.

00:46:22.280 --> 00:46:27.740
And I agree that you should have a pretty broad base, but I feel like marketing yourself.

00:46:27.740 --> 00:46:34.100
Like if you don't have a specialization, if you don't have a focus, if you don't have a very clear message, it's going to be really difficult.

00:46:34.360 --> 00:46:55.320
And one of the examples I like to use is if you were convicted of a crime, let's say murder, would you go to hire a lawyer who dabbles in family law and does some tax stuff and maybe does some criminal law here or there, right?

00:46:55.320 --> 00:46:56.480
It's a generalist, right?

00:46:56.480 --> 00:47:00.040
You would not trust them with the rest of your life.

00:47:00.040 --> 00:47:00.660
It's crazy, right?

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:02.100
Yeah, it's crazy, right?

00:47:02.100 --> 00:47:09.980
So you would say, I want the best criminal defense attorney that specializes in murder cases, right, that you can find.

00:47:09.980 --> 00:47:11.780
You want that specialist, right?

00:47:11.780 --> 00:47:20.280
Even if the journalist could do just as a good job and you're like, well, you know, the journalist could say, well, I know all kinds of law.

00:47:20.980 --> 00:47:25.300
You're like, no, no, no, no, just give me the criminal defense lawyer, please, right?

00:47:25.300 --> 00:47:26.440
You want that specialist guy.

00:47:26.440 --> 00:47:35.440
And the criminal defense lawyer, he might have experience with tax law and divorce law and all that stuff, but he's not going to advertise it that way.

00:47:35.440 --> 00:47:37.660
And that's how—and that's the thing.

00:47:37.660 --> 00:47:40.960
It's like when you are—again, it's shifting the mindset, right?

00:47:40.960 --> 00:47:44.780
As an employee, sometimes we have this mindset of I need to know all this stuff.

00:47:44.860 --> 00:47:49.240
But as an employer, someone hiring you, it's the same thing.

00:47:49.240 --> 00:47:55.900
They're like, well, you know, I've got this application that I need to get built and it costs me money to build this thing.

00:47:55.900 --> 00:47:59.040
I want the person that can do it, right?

00:47:59.040 --> 00:48:03.020
I'm building this, you know, whatever it is, framework.

00:48:03.020 --> 00:48:06.140
You know, I'm using this—I'm building this new Angular app.

00:48:06.320 --> 00:48:08.320
I want an expert in Angular, right?

00:48:08.320 --> 00:48:11.440
So I think that it's critical.

00:48:11.440 --> 00:48:17.820
And when you think about it, if you want to build the highest rate, if you want to get the best job, it's going to be—it's going to go to a specialist.

00:48:17.820 --> 00:48:19.880
Being a specialist is important.

00:48:19.880 --> 00:48:24.480
So it's important to pick some area that you are going to become the expert in.

00:48:24.480 --> 00:48:28.400
And there's so many—I mean, there's so many different reasons why this is true.

00:48:28.400 --> 00:48:39.640
One other major thing is that if you can be the best in the world at a particular thing, and it can be a really small thing, there's a huge, huge advantage for being number one, right?

00:48:39.640 --> 00:48:42.280
I mean, you're going to get the invites to speak at the conferences.

00:48:42.280 --> 00:48:43.860
You can write the book on the subject.

00:48:43.860 --> 00:48:48.300
You can, you know, have the coaching or consulting business.

00:48:48.300 --> 00:48:54.220
Or you can have the blog where whenever anyone types in this particular keyword, it comes to you.

00:48:54.220 --> 00:48:56.460
So you can build a reputation much faster.

00:48:56.460 --> 00:49:03.860
You always want to be the big fish in the small pond, especially when you're starting out, rather than being the small fish in the big pond.

00:49:03.860 --> 00:49:06.420
Because it's going to take you so long to get momentum.

00:49:06.420 --> 00:49:13.040
If you just wanted to be—I think a lot of younger developers that I talk to, they say, well, how could I become a famous software developer?

00:49:13.040 --> 00:49:16.300
And I'm like, well, it's not by being a famous software developer.

00:49:16.440 --> 00:49:22.940
It's by being this person who specifically—they're the best at this particular framework.

00:49:22.940 --> 00:49:26.640
You know, you build your reputation that way.

00:49:26.640 --> 00:49:37.180
That's a lot easier to make ground, to become an expert in a particular market, a particular technology, than it is to just be a generalist, you know, a technologist.

00:49:37.180 --> 00:49:40.980
That would be probably the hardest way to build a name for yourself.

00:49:40.980 --> 00:49:46.420
Instead, pick that small, small specialization where you don't have competition.

00:49:46.420 --> 00:49:48.480
Because you can easily become number one.

00:49:48.480 --> 00:49:55.480
And that's going to be—not only is it going to help your career, but it's going to give you so many options that you didn't have before.

00:49:55.480 --> 00:50:07.700
Yeah, I think that's really interesting and almost counterintuitive in some ways by focusing down, and at least from the way you present yourself, not necessarily what you know, but the way you present yourself to the world.

00:50:08.080 --> 00:50:13.740
By saying, I'm going to focus on this thing, actually more opportunities open up rather than say, I can do anything.

00:50:13.740 --> 00:50:20.180
Once you kind of become the person who can do anything, you're thrown in with everybody, and you kind of just get lost in the sea.

00:50:20.180 --> 00:50:20.580
Exactly.

00:50:21.260 --> 00:50:23.960
And people don't really believe you can do anything, right?

00:50:23.960 --> 00:50:30.640
I mean, that's—as developers, we know that you can be—you can't know everything, but you can be really, really good.

00:50:30.640 --> 00:50:34.440
But people will never really believe you're as good as you are when you claim.

00:50:34.440 --> 00:50:38.560
But when you claim to be an expert in a particular thing, they're more likely to buy that.

00:50:38.620 --> 00:50:51.840
Yeah, especially if you have evidence, like a blog recorded public speaking on, like, some conference, and they put the videos, like PyCon or NDC Oslo or something like that.

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:57.120
They put the videos online, and you can say, here is the video of me presenting for an hour on this.

00:50:57.120 --> 00:51:00.300
Here is my blog with 20 articles on this.

00:51:00.300 --> 00:51:06.340
Just go type this word into Google, and you will see my name and my word come up next to it.

00:51:06.340 --> 00:51:12.120
And then that's almost like, you know, you talked about getting the personal recommendation through the back channel.

00:51:12.120 --> 00:51:15.480
This is like the personal recommendation to people you don't know.

00:51:15.480 --> 00:51:16.160
Exactly.

00:51:16.160 --> 00:51:21.520
And, you know, and the first thing that someone's going to do when you apply for a job anyway is they're going to Google your name.

00:51:21.520 --> 00:51:31.000
And when it comes up and there's like a YouTube video of you speaking at a conference and your blog comes up and all this stuff, you just got the job.

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:35.760
Now they're interviewing you as a formality to find out if you're crazy or not.

00:51:35.760 --> 00:51:36.820
Right?

00:51:36.820 --> 00:51:42.220
But, you know, that's so much better because they might spend an hour reading your blog or watching your video.

00:51:42.220 --> 00:51:45.280
That's more time than you would have at a face-to-face interview.

00:51:45.280 --> 00:51:48.580
And you've got the proof, the social proof.

00:51:48.580 --> 00:51:53.900
You've got better than anything that you could possibly do at an interview or put on your resume.

00:51:54.220 --> 00:51:56.320
So that's why it's so critical.

00:51:56.320 --> 00:51:56.860
Yeah.

00:51:56.860 --> 00:52:08.360
One of the things that a lot of the people on my how to get your first job segment that I did previously last year that I had one half where it was new people and their experience of getting their first job.

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:12.640
The other half was people who do the hiring at like Netflix and PayPal and so on.

00:52:12.640 --> 00:52:18.640
And they all said, look, we're going to go to your GitHub repository and look at your check-in and your repos.

00:52:18.640 --> 00:52:21.060
And, you know, also other things, right?

00:52:21.060 --> 00:52:24.400
Like searching for you, looking at your blogs, looking at your presentations.

00:52:24.400 --> 00:52:27.080
And you can't fake that stuff.

00:52:27.080 --> 00:52:29.700
You can't decide, I want to get that job.

00:52:30.200 --> 00:52:33.320
So I'm going to go put stuff on my GitHub that looks relevant.

00:52:33.320 --> 00:52:35.060
Like that has a history over years.

00:52:35.060 --> 00:52:38.480
And you have to be building towards that, right?

00:52:38.480 --> 00:52:38.920
Exactly.

00:52:38.920 --> 00:52:39.340
Yeah.

00:52:39.340 --> 00:52:39.740
Yeah.

00:52:39.740 --> 00:52:43.300
So we're getting a little towards the end of our time to talk.

00:52:43.300 --> 00:52:54.160
What advice can you give people about marketing yourself in starting down this path where if somebody Googles some aspect of some framework or whatever, like you become the person for that?

00:52:54.160 --> 00:53:02.100
What handful of things would you say to developers, even as full-time employees, that they should be doing to sort of boost their brand, if you will?

00:53:02.100 --> 00:53:02.560
Okay.

00:53:02.560 --> 00:53:10.040
So I would say, you know, first of all, the easiest thing that I think most developers can do that's very accessible, especially in the development world, is to create a blog.

00:53:10.040 --> 00:53:11.460
This is pretty simple.

00:53:11.460 --> 00:53:14.100
You know, this is something – I've got a free course on it.

00:53:14.100 --> 00:53:18.520
If you just go to simpleprogrammer.com, you'll see a pop-up that you can sign up.

00:53:18.520 --> 00:53:22.460
But it's an email course, and it gives you the step-by-step directions on how to do this.

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:27.560
Every developer should have a blog that they keep and they update regularly.

00:53:27.560 --> 00:53:30.860
That's the first thing, and it's for a couple of reasons.

00:53:30.860 --> 00:53:44.680
One of the big ones is because when they go with your name and then your blog comes up and it's updated regularly and it has good content on there, that's a really, really good way to – if it's in writing, it seems more relevant too, right?

00:53:44.680 --> 00:53:53.760
So if you have a blog and it's got your opinions on there and you've got good information on there, that's going to be more better than any interview.

00:53:54.480 --> 00:54:01.580
But, you know, if you really want to boost up your brand, what you should really aim to do is – again, we talked about the specialization.

00:54:01.580 --> 00:54:03.120
But you should pick out your niche.

00:54:03.120 --> 00:54:04.400
What is it going to be?

00:54:04.400 --> 00:54:09.780
And you should try to be everywhere whenever anyone searches on that topic.

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:19.660
So whatever niche that you want to specialize in, if you can show up on as many mediums as possible, that's going to create a really strong branding connection.

00:54:19.900 --> 00:54:35.060
For example, if you found my book or you found my blog and then later on you hear me on a podcast or you find my podcast or you find a YouTube video, you're like, oh, this is – I just listened to this guy.

00:54:35.060 --> 00:54:39.640
Suddenly it connects and someone remembers your name and they're like, oh, I heard this person before.

00:54:39.640 --> 00:54:45.120
And now, you know, if someone hears you from two sources, two different mediums, you're famous instantly.

00:54:45.120 --> 00:54:48.540
And that's – because that's what we were associating in our head, right?

00:54:48.540 --> 00:54:57.060
If you think about it in yourself, right, and you think about the people that you know that are, quote, famous to you, it's because you heard them on two or three different sources.

00:54:57.060 --> 00:54:59.180
And that's critical.

00:54:59.180 --> 00:55:10.140
So that's what really builds a brand that I've discovered is that if you can get out there in multiple mediums and when people have multiple exposures to you, then they're going to really – it's really going to connect.

00:55:10.140 --> 00:55:14.960
Especially if someone can talk to someone else and they say, oh, this guy, I read his blog.

00:55:14.960 --> 00:55:16.280
Oh, I know that guy.

00:55:16.280 --> 00:55:17.680
Bam, you're in.

00:55:17.680 --> 00:55:20.380
So you want to try and build those type of things.

00:55:20.380 --> 00:55:24.480
And the best way to do it is to pick a really good niche, a good specialization.

00:55:24.480 --> 00:55:34.820
And then I would say that, you know, the third thing I would say is your primary – you know, the way that I view marketing and branding yourself and really is a positive light.

00:55:34.820 --> 00:55:40.860
It's not sending out spam emails with advertising Viagra pills, right, unsolicited.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:42.700
It's creating value for people.

00:55:42.700 --> 00:55:48.340
If you go out there and you create a bunch of free value for people, you will get a return.

00:55:48.920 --> 00:55:54.040
I always say that I give away 90% of what I do for free and I charge for 10% of it.

00:55:54.040 --> 00:56:00.520
And that's because that's the best marketing that you could possibly do is to give people free value.

00:56:00.520 --> 00:56:03.940
Because when you do that, then they share it.

00:56:03.940 --> 00:56:05.380
They're like, oh, this guy is awesome.

00:56:05.380 --> 00:56:06.180
He's smart, right?

00:56:06.220 --> 00:56:20.220
They want more from you and they'll eventually, if you're selling something, they'll buy something from you or they'll hire you or they'll, you know, they're going to want to do business with you because you've built trust because they know they've already gotten something valuable from you.

00:56:20.220 --> 00:56:22.760
So I would say, you know, go out there and try to create as much value.

00:56:22.880 --> 00:56:24.860
How can you contribute to the world?

00:56:24.860 --> 00:56:26.340
What thing can you create?

00:56:26.340 --> 00:56:33.780
What information can you put out there in a blog, in YouTube video, podcast, whatever it is that is going to create value for people?

00:56:33.780 --> 00:56:36.320
And don't worry about what you're going to get back, right?

00:56:36.320 --> 00:56:39.660
I mean, I'm not saying do everything for free and be a charity case.

00:56:39.660 --> 00:56:44.960
What I'm saying is that you create most of what you do for free.

00:56:44.960 --> 00:56:49.080
You focus on creating value and by doing that, you will build up an audience.

00:56:49.080 --> 00:56:50.220
You'll build up a reputation.

00:56:50.460 --> 00:56:53.700
And when you have that, then you have, then you can sell something.

00:56:53.700 --> 00:56:55.080
Then you can get the job.

00:56:55.080 --> 00:56:56.980
Then you can, you know, cash in the check.

00:56:56.980 --> 00:57:00.940
But you got to put a lot of deposits in the bank account before you can make a withdrawal.

00:57:00.940 --> 00:57:01.800
Yeah, absolutely.

00:57:01.800 --> 00:57:09.460
And that could be like videos you put on YouTube, that's tutorials showing people how to be really successful with whatever area you're trying to focus on.

00:57:09.460 --> 00:57:11.360
It could also be open source projects, right?

00:57:11.360 --> 00:57:16.280
Like the Python community is really, really values open source contributions.

00:57:16.480 --> 00:57:22.080
So if you had a very popular open source project, that's a huge foot in the door as well.

00:57:22.080 --> 00:57:22.380
Oh, yeah.

00:57:22.380 --> 00:57:24.660
Yeah, I definitely think that's true.

00:57:24.660 --> 00:57:27.500
That's one area that I hadn't focused on personally.

00:57:27.500 --> 00:57:32.000
I don't have much out there in the open source world, but it's a huge, huge opportunity.

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:44.720
There's a lot of, you hear a lot of success stories where people who had contributed to open source projects or started a major open source project have really had successful careers from that.

00:57:44.720 --> 00:57:45.960
So I totally agree.

00:57:45.960 --> 00:57:46.700
Yeah, absolutely.

